      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix: recover MCP OAuth sessions after token refresh",
        "body": "Closes #98377.\n\n## What Problem This Solves\nLong-running gateway MCP sessions could stay stuck after OAuth access-token expiry when the refreshed bearer was rejected on the old streamable HTTP MCP session.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\nThe session MCP runtime now treats OAuth streamable HTTP 401s as stale-session failures, retires the current MCP transport once, rebuilds the catalog/session, and replays the request through the existing refresh-token path. Static-header and non-OAuth MCP failures keep the existing failure/backoff behavior.\n\n## User Impact\nHeadless gateways can recover OAuth-protected remote MCP servers without requiring a manual `openclaw mcp login` while a valid refresh token exists.\n\n## Evidence\nAdded deterministic streamable HTTP OAuth regressions for catalog refresh, direct tool calls, and failed retry/backoff preservation.",
